{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_013UVTLwxWVeDtFQ2RErn3La","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior carefully using the key questions framework.\n\n**Behavior 1: Wait time doubles with each consecutive failure, up to a configured maximum.**\n- MOCK-MISS: This is pure algorithmic logic — computing doubling backoff times. Single function logic.\n- REAL-INFRA: No OS/network needed. Just testing the backoff calculation.\n- LLM-DEP: No.\n- MULTI-STEP: No.\n- This is Unit level. The failure is in the math/logic of doubling up to max.\n\n\n**Behavior 2: Retry logic correctly identifies a rate-limit response and computes appropriate wait time.**\n- For this one, I'm checking whether the code can recognize a 429 status code and calculate the corresponding wait duration. This combines response parsing with backoff computation, so it's still a single module concern that doesn't require real infrastructure — just a mocked HTTP response. The test failure would pinpoint either the recognition logic or the calculation itself.\n\n**Behavior 3: After the wait, the client actually resends the original request and returns the successful result transparently.**\n- This is where multiple pieces need to work together: the sleep mechanism, the HTTP client, and the retry coordinator all have to coordinate properly. I'd use a mock HTTP client that first returns 429, then 200 on the retry, and verify the sequence of operations. The integration test catches failures at the handoff points between these components.\n\n**Behavior 4: After max retries, returns typed QuotaExhaustedError.**\n- This is straightforward — once we've exhausted our retry attempts, the system should throw the right error type.\n\n**Behavior 5: Full retry chain terminates correctly and does not loop indefinitely.**\n- The entire retry mechanism needs to work together without getting stuck. I'd test this at the integration level with mocked HTTP responses to ensure the full chain completes properly.\n\n**Behavior 6: Concurrent...**\n\nFor concurrent requests sharing a quota bucket, I need to verify that multiple async callers are actually reading and writing to the same quota instance. With mocked HTTP responses simulating rate limits, I can check that the shared state is properly managed across concurrent tasks — this is definitely integration-level testing.\n\n**Behavior 7: Requests dispatched in order they were submitted (FIFO ordering).**\n\nTesting that concurrent requests maintain their submission order requires integration-level testing with mock HTTP to verify the ordering behavior.\n\nNow reconsidering the first two behaviors: the exponential backoff formula itself is pure unit-testable math, but identifying a rate-limit response and computing the wait time sits at the unit/integration boundary. Parsing the 429 status and Retry-After header involves response handling that flows into the wait calculation, so I'd classify it as integration. Though if \"identifies a rate-limit response\" just means checking the status code directly, that could be a simple unit test.\n\nLooking at the full picture, I'm settling on unit tests for the backoff algorithm and response parsing logic, then integration tests for the retry loop interactions, error handling across modules, the full termination chain, concurrent state management, and ordering guarantees under concurrency. Let me assign confidence levels to each.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9850,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9850},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"fb4c5c78-db83-478e-a5fa-8df59a3d2294","uuid":"c6cd3166-6c51-407e-9c98-e4caffda5e64"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_013UVTLwxWVeDtFQ2RErn3La","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01DCWAj7Rx2cHBLK2HCTsu99","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Wait time between retries doubles with each consecutive failure, up to a configured maximum.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: This is a pure algorithmic computation — f(n) = min(base × 2^n, cap). The failure mode lives entirely inside one function's math, not at a module handoff. REAL-INFRA: No HTTP, OS, or subprocess needed; the function takes a retry count and returns a duration. MOCK-HIDE: Nothing to mock — the algorithm is self-contained. REJECTION-GATE for Integration: no module boundary is crossed; a single call with a retry-count argument fully exercises the failure.","test_description":"Call the backoff-computation function (or method) with retry counts 0–N+1, where N is the configured cap. Assert that each successive value is double the previous, and that all values ≥ the cap are clamped to the cap. No HTTP client or timer involved.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.88,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The retry logic correctly identifies a rate-limit response and computes the appropriate wait time before the next attempt.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: 'Identifies a rate-limit response' means inspecting a response object (status code, headers such as Retry-After). This is parsing logic on an in-memory object. The failure mode is entirely within that parsing + computation step, not at an I/O boundary. REAL-INFRA: A constructed mock response object (plain TypeScript object matching the interface) reproduces the exact failure — no real HTTP needed. REJECTION-GATE for Integration: the behavior does not describe a failure that only appears when the HTTP client hands off a real response; it describes a classification/calculation rule that can be verified with a stub response.","test_description":"Construct stub response objects (status 429 with a Retry-After header, 429 without, and a non-rate-limit status). Pass each to the rate-limit detection function. Assert correct boolean classification and that the extracted wait time matches the Retry-After value (or the backoff default when the header is absent).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.8,"Integration":0.18,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"After the wait, the client actually resends the original request and returns the successful result to the caller transparently.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure here is not in the backoff calculation — it is in whether the retry coordinator (a) invokes the sleep/timer module, (b) then calls the HTTP module again with the identical request, and (c) surfaces the 200 payload to the caller. This failure only appears at module handoffs: timer → HTTP dispatch → response propagation. A Unit test on any individual piece cannot catch a wiring bug (e.g., sleeping correctly but passing a mutated request on retry). REAL-INFRA: A fake HTTP client returning 429 then 200 fully reproduces the failure; no real network needed. REJECTION-GATE for System: an in-process stub sequence [429, 200] catches the exact regression without real HTTP.","test_description":"Wire the retry client with a fake HTTP transport that returns HTTP 429 on the first call and HTTP 200 with a known payload on the second. Stub/spy the sleep primitive. Assert: (1) sleep was called with the correct duration, (2) the second request carries the identical headers/body as the first, (3) the resolved Promise value equals the 200 payload.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.87,"System":0.07,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"After the configured maximum number of retries, the client returns a typed QuotaExhaustedError rather than a generic error.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure appears when the retry loop exhausts its counter and the error-surfacing path runs. Verifying the correct error type requires the counter, the loop, and the error-construction code to all cooperate — a multi-module interaction. Unit-testing just the error constructor would miss a bug where the loop throws the wrong error type or re-throws the raw HTTP error. REAL-INFRA: A fake transport always returning 429 fully reproduces the failure. REJECTION-GATE for System: the failure is in loop termination and typed error propagation, not in real network behavior.","test_description":"Configure the client with maxRetries = 3. Wire a fake HTTP transport that always returns 429. Call `client.call()` and await the rejection. Assert: the rejected value is an instance of `QuotaExhaustedError` (not `Error` or `HttpError`), and that the transport was called exactly maxRetries + 1 times.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.85,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The full retry chain — initial call, backoff retries, quota tracking — terminates correctly and does not loop indefinitely before surfacing the error.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: Infinite-loop bugs live in the interaction among the retry counter, the quota tracker, and the loop condition — none of these modules alone can exhibit indefinite looping. The failure only surfaces when the orchestration layer is assembled. REAL-INFRA: A fake transport always returning 429 with a Jest fake-timer wrapping the sleep fully reproduces the failure. REJECTION-GATE for System: the termination invariant is about control flow across modules, not about real network or OS behavior. MOCK-HIDE: If we only unit-test the counter in isolation, a bug in how the loop reads the counter is invisible.","test_description":"Configure the client with small maxRetries (e.g., 2) and a fake transport always returning 429. Use fake/accelerated timers. Call `client.call()` and assert the Promise rejects within a bounded number of transport calls (maxRetries + 1) and that no test timeout occurs. Also assert the final error is `QuotaExhaustedError`.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.04,"Integration":0.88,"System":0.07,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"Requests issued concurrently from multiple async callers in the same process all draw from the same shared quota bucket.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure is a shared-state bug: two callers holding separate references to independent quota buckets instead of a single shared instance, or race conditions in shared counter updates. This only surfaces when multiple async tasks are wired to the same client instance and fire concurrently. REAL-INFRA: In-process async concurrency with a fake transport can reproduce this exactly — no real HTTP or OS needed. REJECTION-GATE for System: the shared-state failure is about JavaScript's single-threaded async model and instance identity, not about real network conditions. MOCK-HIDE: Testing each caller in isolation always passes; the bug only appears under concurrent in-process dispatch.","test_description":"Create one client instance with a fake transport. Launch N concurrent `client.call()` Promises without awaiting individually. Instrument the quota bucket to record how many times it is decremented and which instance is referenced. Assert that all N calls reference the same bucket instance and that total decrements equal N (not N per caller).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.04,"Integration":0.88,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"When multiple requests are waiting to be sent, they are dispatched in the order they were originally submitted.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: FIFO ordering is an emergent property of the queue data structure, the dispatch loop, and concurrent async scheduling all working together. A unit test on the queue alone cannot catch a bug where the dispatch loop drains in arrival order but the HTTP calls resolve in a different order, or where the queue is bypassed for ready-state requests. REAL-INFRA: An in-process fake transport that records call order and a controlled async scheduler reproduce the failure. REJECTION-GATE for System: ordering is determined by in-process queue management, not real network timing. MOCK-HIDE: Testing only queue push/pop misses wiring bugs between the queue and the HTTP dispatch loop.","test_description":"Submit N requests (tagged 1…N) to the client simultaneously while the fake transport is paused/held. Release the transport. Record the order in which the transport receives each request. Assert the transport call order matches submission order 1…N.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.87,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.02}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9850,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9850},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"fb4c5c78-db83-478e-a5fa-8df59a3d2294","uuid":"cc7ca7ea-73b5-4810-9e61-d44d03f31317"}
